"Sexton P.F., Norris R.D., Wilson P.A., Pälike H., Westerhold T., Röhl U., Bolton C.T., Gibbs S.","Eocene global warming events driven by ventilation of oceanic dissolved organic carbon",2011,"Nature","471","7338",,"349","353",,,10.1038/nature09826,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79952800025&partnerID=40&md5=0e918f56b869081a631d6c60433b2a5c","Scripps Institution of Oceanography, University of California, San Diego, CA 92093, United States; National Oceanography Centre Southampton, University of Southampton, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom; MARUM-Center for Marine Environmental Sciences, University of Bremen, Leobener Strasse, 28359 Bremen, Germany; Department of Earth and Environmental Sciences, Open University, Milton Keynes MK7 6AA, United Kingdom; Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Oviedo, 33005 Oviedo, Spain","Sexton, P.F., Scripps Institution of Oceanography, University of California, San Diego, CA 92093, United States, National Oceanography Centre Southampton, University of Southampton, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom, Department of Earth and Environmental Sciences, Open University, Milton Keynes MK7 6AA, United Kingdom; Norris, R.D., Scripps Institution of Oceanography, University of California, San Diego, CA 92093, United States; Wilson, P.A., National Oceanography Centre Southampton, University of Southampton, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom; Pälike, H., National Oceanography Centre Southampton, University of Southampton, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom; Westerhold, T., MARUM-Center for Marine Environmental Sciences, University of Bremen, Leobener Strasse, 28359 Bremen, Germany; Röhl, U., MARUM-Center for Marine Environmental Sciences, University of Bremen, Leobener Strasse, 28359 Bremen, Germany; Bolton, C.T., National Oceanography Centre Southampton, University of Southampton, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom, Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Oviedo, 33005 Oviedo, Spain; Gibbs, S., National Oceanography Centre Southampton, University of Southampton, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom","Hyperthermals- are intervals of rapid, pronounced global warming known from six episodes within the Palaeocene and Eocene epochs (∼465-34 million years (Myr) ago). The most extreme hyperthermal was the ∼4170 thousand year (kyr) interval of 5-7 °C global warming during the Palaeocene-Eocene Thermal Maximum (PETM, 56Myr ago). The PETM is widely attributed to massive release of greenhouse gases from buried sedimentary carbon reservoirs, and other, comparatively modest, hyperthermals have also been linked to the release of sedimentary carbon. Here we show, using new 2.4-Myr-long Eocene deep ocean records, that the comparatively modest hyperthermals are much more numerous than previously documented, paced by the eccentricity of Earth-s orbit and have shorter durations (∼440kyr) and more rapid recovery phases than the PETM. These findings point to the operation of fundamentally different forcing and feedback mechanisms than for the PETM, involving redistribution of carbon among Earth-s readily exchangeable surface reservoirs rather than carbon exhumation from, and subsequent burial back into, the sedimentary reservoir. Specifically, we interpret our records to indicate repeated, large-scale releases of dissolved organic carbon (at least 1,600 gigatonnes) from the ocean by ventilation (strengthened oxidation) of the ocean interior. The rapid recovery of the carbon cycle following each Eocene hyperthermal strongly suggests that carbon was re-sequestered by the ocean, rather than the much slower process of silicate rock weathering proposed for the PETM. Our findings suggest that these pronounced climate warming events were driven not by repeated releases of carbon from buried sedimentary sources, but, rather, by patterns of surficial carbon redistribution familiar from younger intervals of Earth history. © 2011 Macmillan Publishers Limited. All rights reserved.",,"organic carbon; carbon; comparative study; deep sea; dissolved organic carbon; Eocene; global warming; greenhouse gas; marine environment; orbit determination; paleoclimate; paleoenvironment; reservoir; sedimentary structure; temperature effect; ventilation; weathering; article; carbon cycle; Eocene; feedback system; geology; greenhouse effect; oxidation; Paleocene; priority journal; sea; Atlantic Ocean; Atmosphere; Carbon Cycle; Foraminifera; Geologic Sediments; Global Warming; History, Ancient; Oceans and Seas; Seawater; Temperature",,,,,,"Zachos, J.C., Rohl, U., Schellenberg, S.A., Sluijs, A., Hodell, D.A., Kelly, D.C., Thomas, E., Kroon, D., Paleoclimate: Rapid acidification of the ocean during the paleocene-eocene thermal maximum (2005) Science, 308 (5728), pp. 1611-1615. , DOI 10.1126/science.1109004; Röhl, U., Westerhold, T., Bralower, T.J., Zachos, J.C., On the duration of the Paleocene-Eocene thermal maximum (PETM) (2007) Geochem. Geophys. Geosyst., 8, pp. Q12002; Zachos, J.C., Dickens, G.R., Zeebe, R.E., An early Cenozoic perspective on greenhouse warming and carbon-cycle dynamics (2008) Nature, 451, pp. 279-283; Thomas, E., Zachos, J.C., Bralower, T.J., (2000) Warm Climates in Earth History, pp. 132-160. , (eds Huber, B., MacLeod, K. & Wing, S.) Cambridge Univ. Press; Cramer, B.S., Wright, J.D., Kent, D.V., Aubry, M.P., Orbital climate forcing of d13C excursions in the late Paleocene-early Eocene (chrons C24n-C25n) (2003) Paleoceanography, 18, p. 1097. , doi:10.1029/2003PA000909; Lourens, L.J., Sluijs, A., Kroon, D., Zachos, J.C., Thomas, E., Rohl, U., Bowles, J., Raffi, I., Astronomical pacing of late Palaeocene to early Eocene global warming events (2005) Nature, 435 (7045), pp. 1083-1087. , DOI 10.1038/nature03814; Petrizzo, M.R., An early late Paleocene event on Shatsky Rise, northwest Pacific Ocean (ODP Leg 198): Evidence fromplanktonic foraminiferal assemblages (2005) Proc. ODP Sci. Res